"1509","1506":"1506","about 1450":"circa 1450","1405":"1405","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Osgodby, Lincolnshire, England":"Osgodby, Lincolnshire, England","Osgodby, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England","Osgodby, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Osgodby, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1423–1506":"1423–1506","1444–1488":"1444–1488","1450–1509":"1450–1509","1459–1532":"1459–1532","1400–Male":"1400–Deceased","1405–Female":"1405–Deceased","1471/1472":"from 10 January 1471 to 9 January 1473","1450":"1450","1459":"1459","1423":"1423","27 April 1459":"27 April 1459","1488":"1488","1422":"1422","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1532":"1532","1444":"1444","1509":"1509","1506":"1506","about 1450":"about 1450","1405":"1405","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Osgodby, Lincolnshire, England":"Osgodby, Lincolnshire, England","Osgodby, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Osgodby, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Osgodby, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":32,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Langholme was born in 1423, in Osgodby, Yorkshire, England, her father, John Langholme, was 23 and her mother, F Langholme, was 18. She married William de Armyne from 10 January 1471 to 9 January 1473, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1506, in Yorkshire, England, at the age of 83."},"et":{"1423–1506":"1423–1506","1444–1488":"1444–1488","1450–1509":"1450–1509","1459–1532":"1459–1532","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","1405–Female":"1405–Surnud","1471/1472":"10. jaanuar 1471 kuni 9. jaanuar 1473","1450":"1450","1459":"1459","1423":"1423","27 April 1459":"27. aprill 1459","1488":"1488","1422":"1422","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1532":"1532","1444":"1444","1509":"1509","1506":"1506","about 1450":"umbes 1450","1405":"1405","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Osgodby, Lincolnshire, England":"Osgodby, Lincolnshire, England","Osgodby, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Osgodby, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Osgodby, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1423–1506":"1423–1506","1444–1488":"1444–1488","1450–1509":"1450–1509","1459–1532":"1459–1532","1400–Male":"1400–Kuollut","1405–Female":"1405–Kuollut","1471/1472":"vuodesta 10. tammikuuta 1471 vuoteen 9. tammikuuta 1473","1450":"1450","1459":"1459","1423":"1423","27 April 1459":"27. huhtikuuta 1459","1488":"1488","1422":"1422","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1532":"1532","1444":"1444","1509":"1509","1506":"1506","about 1450":"noin 1450","1405":"1405","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Osgodby, Lincolnshire, England":"Osgodby, Lincolnshire, England","Osgodby, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England","Osgodby, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Osgodby, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1423–1506":"1423–1506","1444–1488":"1444–1488","1450–1509":"1450–1509","1459–1532":"1459–1532","1400–Male":"1400–Décédé","1405–Female":"1405–D